        <exercise id="fs-id1169738137564" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1169738137566">    <para id="import-auto-id1169737761163">A 2.50-m-diameter university communications satellite dish receives TV signals that have a maximum electric field strength (for one channel) of <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>7</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>50</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mrow><m:mi fontstyle="italic">μ</m:mi><m:mn>V/m</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{7 "." "50" mV/m} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. (See <link target-id="import-auto-id1169738077918"/>.) (a) What is the intensity of this wave? (b) What is the power received by the antenna? (c) If the orbiting satellite broadcasts uniformly over an area of <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>50</m:mtext><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>13</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msup><m:mtext> m</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{1 "." "50"´"10" rSup { size 8{"13"} } " m" rSup { size 8{2} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> (a large fraction of North America), how much power does it radiate?</para><figure id="import-auto-id1169738077918"><media id="import-auto-id1169738077919" alt="A large, round dish antenna looking like a giant white saucer is shown. It rests on a pillar like structure based on the ground. It is shown to receive TV signals in the form of electromagnetic waves shown as wavy arrows.">
